Reposting a story idea from the very end of the last thread.

>Be anon
>You're a doctor in an 1870s frontier town populated with both humans and anthros
>Everyone usually gets along pretty well but it's not uncommon for Wild West style shenanigans to happen
>Your life is quiet, and that's exactly how you want it
>One day there's a gunfight in the middle of town
>Miraculously, only one person is seriously injured. A tigress
>It takes three people, yourself included, to carry her in. She has to be nearly seven feet tall, every bit of her tensed and coiled tight as a loaded spring
>She's been shot twice in the back and though nobody saw *exactly* what happened, it looks like she was bushwhacked
>You ask the barely conscious tigress her name but she just rolls her eyes before passing out
>You work tirelessly through the night to save your mysterious patient and just barely manage to stabilize her
>Even then it's touch and go for a few days before she regains full lucidity
>Haltingly, she thanks you for saving her life and comments that you must have removed a lot of bullets in your time on the frontier
>There actually isn't nearly as much gun violence as you'd think. Your own medical skills were honed during the (civil) war, but you don't like talking about that
>The tigress, at least somewhat influenced by the morphine in her system, grabs you by the collar and pulls you close
>For a moment you're sure you're about to lose your face, but instead the tigress stares you in the eyes, your nose nearly touching hers, and tells you very gravely that she'd have killed the son-of-a-bitch if his hired men hadn't shot her in the back first
>You don't know who the 'son-of-a-bitch' is but nod along anyway
>The tigress lets you go, satisfied that you understand, and drifts off again
>...You're beginning to suspect that your patient is involved in something much more serious than a simple shooting
